{"/service/ndnp/nbu/batch_nbu_bluejay_ver02/data/2023271000/0051701414A/1945082401/0649.xml":{"full_text":"THE POWDER KEG\nWeekly Newspaper of\nNAVAL AMMUNITION DEPOT\nHastings, Nebraska\nPublished weekly from appropriated BuOrd funds in accordance\nwith SecNavltr. EXOS; AO (Pub) WBW: bmcd, of 28 May 1945\n(NDB 45-526), for the benefit of Naval and civilian personnel, and\nprinted at Naval Depot Print Shop, Hastings, Nebraska.\nCaptain Allan W. Ashbrook, U. S. N\u201e COMMANDING\nCommander B. E. Carter, U. S. N., Executive Officer\nLieutenant R. L. Miller, U. S. N. R., Public Relations Officer\nLyman L. Winter, Sic, Editor\nKenneth R. Cone, Sic, Associate Editor\nH. F. Smith, Y3c, Sports\nD. Sherwood, SpP3c, Photographer\nThe POWDER KEG receives Camp Newspaper Service Material.\nWhat Are Your Post-War Plans7\nApproximately twenty-five people on the Depot were asked this\nquestion this week: \u201cWhat are your post-war plans?\u201d With hut few\nexceptions the answer was the same, \u201cIf we lose our jobs here we don\u2019t\nhave any plans.\u201d\nIt would seem that this is rather startling when you consider\nthe fact that most people either experienced or know of the after\nmath of World War I, which brought inflation, failures and suffering.\nThen, too, there are many who know what it means to be without a\njob and its accompanying hardships.\nIt\u2019s long been known that life\u2019s philosophy of living from day\nto day, or hand to mouth, is the easy way. Or, let the other fellow\nworry about what happens to me. But, that philosophy brings with\nit unemployment, relief lines and a burden on others, who have planned\na way, to bear the load through increased taxes and personal sacrifice.\nEveryone has known that someday the war would come to a\nclose, that war industry would be reconverted into a peacetime in\ndustry, that many new problems would be created, that we would\nhave a job of reconverting ourselves from some phase of war activity\nto peacetime status. No one or no particular function of the govern\nment is going to take it upon themselves to see that you are comfort\nably situated. This is a job which you must do.\nNaturally, sudden peace caught many people asleep at the\nswitch\u2014not only people but industries. There has been a wholesale\ncancellation of war contracts and all industries, who were not prepar\ning for peace, will be slow to get into peacetime competition. John\nSnyder, Reconversion Director, has stated that there will be an im\nmediate and large dislocation of our economy and that there will be\na sharp but temporary unemployment.\nThe readjustment or reconversion will not be all unpleasant.\nMotorists now have all the gasoline they want. All manpower re\nstrictions have been lifted. Very few people are now hungry, nor are\nthey likely to be. There is enough fuel oil and canned foods.\nThe government would have to change its economy, however,\nif it were to conform to the ideas of millions of Americans. There\nis a grave danger that they have come to believe that the standards\nof our inflated war-time economy can be or should be maintained in\npeacetime, or what we used to term as normal years. There is\nnothing normal about war standards. Prices, wages and spending\nare all geared to the frantic tempo of war. The prosperity that we\nnow know is unreal and unstable. It is created by the deficit spend\ning of our government. Yet it creates a false prosperity which\nmight be used to rally the people to approve more public spending and\nmore debt.\nFlood pressures which are too great will break the stoutest\ndam. By the same token our nation can spend itself into bankruptcy.\nWho Knows\n1. Of 70,000,000 Japanese of all\napes-have been hard at\nwork for the war.\na. 20,000,000 b. 30,000,000\nc. 35,000,000\n2. In their homeland, all Japa\nnese men and women between the\nages of-and_were re\nquired to register for war work.\na. 21-50 b. 12-60 c. 15-65\n3. Jap war workers toiled ap\nproximately _ hours a week.\na. 90 b. 80 c. 70\n4. Outside their homeland the\nJaps controlled a potential labor\nforce of_enslaved people.\na. 40.000,000 b. 100,000,000\nc. 400,000,000\n5. As compared with U. S. war\nproduction, weapons turned out by\nJap war workers were_\na. poor imitations b. good\nimitations c. excellent and often\noriginal.\nA sailor got a letter containing\na sketch of the family car\u2019s instru\nment panel.\n\u201cThis is exactly how the dash\nboard looks,\u201d his wife wrote. \u201cDo\nwe need a quart of oil?\u201d\nInquiring Reporter.\nWith the advent of peace has\ncome the stoppage of production\nfor war all over the country. Work\ners in every type of industry are\nwondering what is happening to\nthem and are trying to make up\ntheir minds, especially the women,\nwhat to do next. Here on the\nDepot, our workers are wondering\nalso\u2014some have already made up\ntheir minds, and some are waiting\nto find out what the Depot has in\nstore for them.\nBecause everyone is thinking\nabout their future activities, I\nthought it interesting to find out\nsome of them; therefore, of some\nof the men and women workers on\nthe Depot, I asked the following\nquestion: \u201cWhat are your plans\nfor the immediate future?\u201d\nIn reply to my question, Mrs.\nEllsworth Armstrong, wife of\nSpecialist A lc Armstrong here on\nthe Depot stated. \u201cI have enjoyed\nworking here very much and plan\nto continue on in my present\ncapacity as secretary to the Wel\nfare and Recreation Officer until\nmy husband is either transferred\nor discharged. When he is finally\ndischarged, we plan to return to\nConnecticut and buy a home of our\nown where I can be what I want\nto be for the rest of my life\u2014a\nhousewife.\nSome of the people I talked\nwith were workers in the Am\nmunition Laundry, and three of\nthese, the Misses Roth, and Mrs.\nRoe, residents of Deweese, Ne\nbraska, have already been inform\ned of their impending release. All\nthree stated that they have enjoy\ned working here and would like\nto continue to do so; however, as\nMrs. Roe put it, \u201cWe realize that\nnot everyone can be kept on here,\nand since we commute every day.\nit is probably best that we should\nbe the ones to go. We are fortun\nate, however, in that we have\npositions already promised in our\nown home town.\u201d\nA Mr. William Markwardt, a\ndry cleaning worker in the same\nestablishment, states, \u201cMy plans\nare simple\u2014I shall work at my\npresent job as long as I am able,\nand 1 have been assured of being\nIt\u2019s My Opinion\nThat things cannot go too rbugh\nly with the Japs. There seems to d\nhave been a lot of stalling for\ntime on their part and I sincerely\nhope that General MacArthur gets\nin there at the earliest possible\nmoment to take over. Personally,\nI would rather have seen Admiral\nHalsey do the job but General\nMacArthur is capable and I\u2019m sure\nconsidering the knowledge he has\nof the Japs, that he will give no\nquarter.\nThe Japs have had everything\ntheir own way for many years in\nthe Pacific and it is going to be\ndifficult for them to be dictated\nto. I think that is one of the\nreasons there has been so much\nstalling for time\u2014they were try\ning to prepare the people for the\ninevitable. The Japs, down to the\nlittle man on the street, learned\nthe cold facts of surrender early\nthis week. They were warned\nagainst wishful thinking and were\ngiven the sugar-coated pill that\nAllied terms may be \u201csomewhat\nlenient.\u201d\nThe Jap has been a vicious\nfighter. Their religious fanaticism\nhas made it doubly tough. Very\nfew prisoners were taken during\nthe many conflicts in the Pacific\nbecause it was their religion to\nfight until dead for the emperor.\nThe atrocities in prison camps have\nbeen known to us for a long time.\nAmerican wives, mothers and\nfathers have not forgotten. It is\nnow time that they pay the penal\nty- 4\nKansas City (CNS)\u2014Joe Infield,\na restless sleeper, got his head\nwedged between the bars of his\nbed. His wife, mother-in-law, a\nneighbor and 2 cops finally freed\nhim with a hack saw.\nkept on.\u201d\nIt seems that our librarian in the\nPermanent Recreation Building\nhad already formulated her plans\nand was leaving the Depot whether\nthe war was over or not. She\nstated, \u201cFor some time I have\nbeen planning to resume my study\nof medicine and shall enter the\nmedical school of the University of\nNebraska next month.\u201d\nGROWTH OF THE NAVY IN WORK! WAR H\nnumh*mn tutor\n7695 IMALVKSCLS\nDetmVNtf ttmiir\n52,179 \u00bbAV*VHULS\n:3tmfn react\"\nAUG.IW-'SUMALUMf\nWO I NAVAL VE5SUS\n51,000 IrtVAl VESSELS\nItfps'M&r'\n>J.8W Wju vessels\nJULY W!''4f\u00abICA\"\n20,111 mki VB5US\nJUKE; IM4-\"5*IPAN*\nSI. 587 KAVAl Vf SKIS\nff|L I945-\"|W JIM'\n60,& UHL VESSELS\nN0V,t9*3-'T*8*W**\n29,66? NAMlVftfElS\nJUUT,\n55,229 NWfcVBSUS\n\u00ab*Y, IWS-DWWVM'\n100,POO MMUKKli","height":"13760","width":"10540"}}
